          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.1197" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Administration</heading>
               <p>OHCHR's Geneva headquarters incorporates the following divisions: Human Rights Council and Treaty Mechanisms; Thematic Engagement, Special Procedures and Right to Development; and Field Operations and Technical Co-operation, as well as an Executive Direction and Management section. There is an office in New York, USA, which focuses on integrating human rights norms and standards throughout the UN.</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="IO-UN.1199" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Field Presences</heading>
               <p>A substantial structure of field presences has been developed to promote human rights, provide technical assistance, as well as to support UN conflict prevention, peacemaking, peacekeeping and peacebuilding activities. OHCHR maintains regional offices in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia (covering East Africa); Bangkok, Thailand (South-East Asia); Beirut, Lebanon (the Middle East and North Africa); Bishkek, Kyrgyzstan (Central Asia); Brussels, Belgium (Europe); Dakar, Senegal (West Africa); Panama City, Panama (Central America); Santiago, Chile (South America); Pretoria, South Africa (Southern Africa); and Suva, Fiji (the Pacific); as well as an OHCHR Sub-Regional Centre for Human Rights and Democracy in Central Africa, based in Yaoundé, Cameroon, and a Training and Documentation Centre for South West Asia and the Arab Region, located in Doha, Qatar. There are 18 country offices; a field-based structure in Seoul (Republic of Korea) focused on the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea; a Human Rights Monitoring Mission in Ukraine; and 10 human rights components of UN-mandated peace missions. In 2023 there were 38 human rights advisers deployed to support UN Country Teams, as well as 13 technical missions.</p>
          </int-org-section>
     </int-org-section>
     <int-org-section id="IO-UN.1201" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
          <heading>Activities</heading>
          <p>OHCHR’s mandate incorporates the promotion and protection of human rights throughout the world; the reinforcement of international co-operation in the field of human rights; the promotion of universal ratification and implementation of international standards; the establishment of a dialogue with governments to ensure respect for human rights; and co-ordination of efforts by other UN programmes and organs to promote respect for human rights. Under the UN Technical Co-operation Programme in the Field of Human Rights, established in 1955, OHCHR assists states, at their request, to strengthen their capacities in the observance of democracy, human rights, and the rule of law. It supports the establishment of independent national human rights institutions; deploys monitoring missions; facilitates the rehabilitation of victims of torture and of slavery; and visits places of detention. The Office studies and responds to cases of serious violations of human rights, and may undertake diplomatic efforts to prevent violations.</p>
          <p>OHCHR’s management programme for 2024-27 had the following six pillars: (i) enhance accountability; (ii) foster participation; (iii) address discrimination; (iv) seek to embed human rights in peace and security; (v) seek to embed human rights in development efforts; and (vi) strengthen support for the core human rights ecosystem. Reinvigorating an effective global human rights movement; enhancing early warning and the global protection agenda in the context of emerging risks; promoting a human rights economy; promoting diversity; promoting rights-based environmental actions; and ensuring that digital technologies and data advance human rights were to be prioritized.</p>
          <p>A Human Rights 75 initiative that was conducted by OHCHR during 2023, to commemorate the 75th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, culminated in December in a high-level event, held in Geneva, that comprised thematic consultations, dialogues, and a `pledging tree’ session focused on commitments aimed at advancing human rights.</p>
          <int-org-section id="OHCHR.IO.TREATYDIV.1" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Human Rights Council and Treaty Mechanisms</heading>
               <p>OHCHR offers support and expertise to the UN’s human rights monitoring mechanisms, including the Human Rights Council (HRC), for which it serves as the secretariat, and the Universal Periodic Review (which assesses, cyclically, the human rights situation in all UN member states).</p>
               <org-list>
                    <org-entry id="IO-UNGA.495" media="PRINTANDONLINE" print-only="NO" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="ORG-ENTRYREF">
                         <org-entry-head>
