               <!--2024 Pres. to be elected c. 10.i.24, from the African group-->
               <p>OHCHR supports the following committees of independent experts (known as `Treaty Bodies’) which monitor the implementation of core international human rights treaties:</p>
               <gen-list>
                    <item>Human Rights Committee: monitors the implementation of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (entered into force in 1976)</item>
                    <item>Committee on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights: monitors the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights (1976)</item>
                    <item>Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination: monitors the International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination (1969)</item>
                    <item>Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women: monitors the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women (1981)</item>
                    <item>Committee Against Torture: monitors the Convention against Torture and Other Cruel, Inhuman or Degrading Treatment or Punishment (1987) and the Optional Protocol of the Convention against Torture (2006); a related Sub-committee, established in 2007, focuses on the prevention of torture</item>
                    <item>Committee on the Rights of the Child: monitors the Convention on the Rights of the Child (1990) and its optional Protocols on Involvement of Children in Armed Conflict (2002), on Sale of Children, Child Prostitution and Child Pornography (2002), and (in effect since April 2014) on a Communications Procedure—allowing individual children to submit complaints about specific violations of their human rights under the Convention</item>
                    <item>Committee on the Protection of the Rights of All Migrant Workers and Members of their Families: monitors the International Convention on the Protection of the Rights of All Migrant Workers and Members of Their Families (2003)</item>
                    <item>Committee on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities: monitors the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (2008), and its Optional Protocol (2008) which gives the Committee competence to analyse complaints over alleged violations of the Convention (by states) that have been submitted to it by individuals</item>
                    <item>Committee on Enforced Disappearances: monitors the International Convention for the Protection of All Persons from Enforced Disappearance (2010).</item>
               </gen-list>
               <p usage="edio">A new intergovernmental working group to consider the possibility of elaborating an international framework on the regulation and oversight of the activities of private military and security companies was approved by the HRC in September 2017 (fifth session: April 2024).</p>
               <p>OHCHR serves as the secretariat of an intergovernmental working group on transnational corporations and other business enterprises that was established by the HRC in June 2014 to draft a legally binding instrument on business activities and human rights, with a focus on ending abuses of labour forces, trafficking in supply chains, attacks against human rights defenders, and environmental pollution. A UN Forum on Business and Human Rights, is convened annually, under OHCHR auspices, with a focus on implementation of the 2011 UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights (12th Forum: November 2023).</p>
               <p>OHCHR also acts as the secretariat for three grant-making humanitarian funds: the UN Voluntary Fund for Victims of Torture (established in 1981); the Voluntary Fund for Indigenous Populations (established in 1985); and the Trust Fund on Contemporary Forms of Slavery (established in 1991).</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="OHCHR.IO.100" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Special Procedures</heading>
               <p>OHCHR supports the work of the thematic and country experts, appointed by the HRC under its so-called Special Procedures. These may undertake field visits, enhance public awareness of a situation, report violations of human rights, and aim to contribute to the development of human rights standards.</p>
               <p>
        At January 2024 46 thematic human rights mandates were active, concerning, 
        <i>inter alia,</i>
         adequate housing; privacy; the promotion and protection of human rights in the context of climate change; the independence of judges and lawyers; discrimination based on contemporary forms of racism, racial discrimination, xenophobia and related intolerance; violence and discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity; discrimination against women and girls; the sale and sexual exploitation of children; transnational corporations and other business enterprises; contemporary forms of slavery; obligations relating to the enjoyment of a safe, clean, healthy and sustainable environment; the right of everyone to the enjoyment of the highest attainable standard of physical and mental health; the effects of foreign debt and other international financial obligations of states; the right to development; cultural rights; education; freedom of opinion and expression; freedom of assembly and association; the rights of people with albinism; leprosy; disabilities; negative impact of unilateral coercive measures; arbitrary detention; enforced disappearances; extrajudicial, summary or arbitrary executions; oversight of the activities of private military and security companies; the use of mercenaries as a means of violating human rights; indigenous peoples; internally displaced people (IDPs); migrants; minority issues; older persons; the human right to food; and the human right to safe drinking water and sanitation.
      </p>
               <p>Other specific focal human rights areas include rule of law; administration of justice; children deprived of liberty; violence against children; trafficking in persons; conscientious objection to military service; corruption; the death penalty; equal participation in political and public affairs; safety of journalists; the rights of people with HIV/AIDS; land and human rights; forced evictions; the right to a nationality; climate change; social security; urbanization; protection of human rights and fundamental freedoms while countering terrorism; and preventing and countering violent extremism.</p>
               <p>Special rapporteurs or independent experts may be appointed to monitor and report on a specific human rights situation. The following country mandates were active at January 2024: Afghanistan (mandate established in 2021); Belarus (2012); Burundi (2021); Cambodia (1993); the Central African Republic (CAR) (2013); North Korea (2004); Eritrea (2012); Iran (2011); Mali (2013); Myanmar (1992); the Palestinian territories (1993, to be maintained pending `the end of the Israeli occupation’); the Russian Federation (2022); Somalia (1993); and Syria (2011).</p>
          </int-org-section>
          <int-org-section id="OHCHR.IO.99" sllink="SLSDOC" slsdocrf="INT-ORG-SECTREF">
               <heading>Ongoing HRC-mandated Investigations</heading>
               <p>OHCHR provides expertise and support to independent investigations mandated by the HRC in response to serious violations of international humanitarian or human rights law either relating to a specific incident or to a protracted situation.</p>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Belarus</heading>
                    <p>In March 2021 the HRC adopted a resolution which requested the Office to carry out a comprehensive examination of all alleged human rights violations committed in Belarus since 1 May 2020, in the context of the run up to and aftermath of that country’s August 2020 presidential election; the resulting report found considerable evidence of human rights violations committed between 1 May 2020 and 31 December 2021. In March 2022 the Office reported that a consistent pattern of arrests, detention, ill treatment, torture, rape and other sexual and gender-based violence, and systematic denial of fair trail rights had been used by the Belarusian authorities to suppress opposition supporters. OHCHR reported that at 31 March 2023 1,462 people remained imprisoned in politically motivated contexts; and that by February of that year the Belarusian authorities had closed 797 non-governmental organizations (NGOs), while 432 other Belarus-based NGOs had dissolved themselves to avoid the risk of prosecution (accounting for most human rights bodies that had been present in the country). The Office reported that new legislation had been introduced by the Belarusian Government aimed at curtailing fundamental freedoms.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="ewyb edio">ITE on the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)</heading>
                    <p>The ITE on the situation in Kasaï (DRC) was tasked by the HRC in June 2017 with collecting and preserving relevant information and determining the facts regarding alleged violations of human rights and of international humanitarian law in that area since 2016. In June 2018 it released a report that found that certain violations perpetrated since 2016 by the DRC military and by the rebel Kamuina Nsapu Bana Mura militias amounted to crimes against humanity and war crimes. In September 2021 the ITE on Kasaï issued a report that noted ongoing intercommunal clashes, food insecurity, soaring urban crime, and a humanitarian crisis that was attributed in part to forced returns to the region of Congolese from Angola. A decision by the DRC Government to decentralize the transitional justice process was welcomed by the ITE. Little progress, however, was reported in combating impunity. In the following month the 48th session of the HRC extended the scope of the ITE’s mandate to cover the whole of the DRC. In August 2022 the ITE recommended that the DRC authorities prioritize the development of a communication strategy to support national efforts to promote transitional justice and combat impunity; establish a centralized biometric identification system to enable systematic background checks in support of the disarmament and demobilization of former combatants; and promptly adopt legislation on the nationwide prevention and punishment of hate speech and incitement to violence or discrimination. In October 2023 the UN General Assembly requested OHCHR to deploy additional transitional justice experts to Ituri, North Kivu, South Kivu and Tanganyika, and to strengthen support for the Truth, Justice and Reconciliation Commission of Kasaï-Central Province. The ITE was requested to submit its final report to the 57th session of the HRC (scheduled to be held in September-October 2024).</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Independent FFM on Iran</heading>
                    <p>In November 2022 the HRC’s 35th special session authorized an Independent FFM to investigate the deteriorating human rights situation in Iran, particularly with respect to women and children. In July 2023 the CoI on Iran confirmed that its investigations would include the targeting and harassment of journalists connected to Iran, and of their families. In September it noted an intensification of state harassment of women and girls.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>OHCHR Democratic People’s Republic of Korea Accountability Project</heading>
                    <p>In accordance with a March 2017 resolution of the HRC a project aimed at advancing accountability in North Korea was initiated, based in Geneva and in Seoul, South Korea. In March 2023 OHCHR issued a report, based on interviews with the relatives of people who had been abducted or forcibly disappeared by the North Korean authorities, which urged the introduction of a comprehensive reparation programmes in such cases.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="ewyb edio">Independent Investigative Mechanism for Myanmar (IIMM)</heading>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio">During March 2017-September 2019 OHCHR supported a formal FFM, authorized by the HRC, that investigated allegations of state-sponsored mass systematic brutal attacks in Myanmar, in particular against Myanma Rohingya from Rakhine State. The CoI’s final report, released in September, emphasized that the 600,000 Rohingya who were still residing within Myanmar were subject to systematic persecution and were living under the threat of genocide, and that the Myanma Government was failing to prevent, to investigate, to criminalize effectively and to punish genocide. At that time the High Commissioner for Human Rights described Myanmar security operations against the Rohingya as `a textbook example of ethnic cleansing’. The FFM report noted that in attempting to quell civilian support for the Arakan Army—which since 2009 had been mounting an insurgency against the Myanma Tatmadaw (military)—the Tatmadaw had restricted humanitarian access to ethnic Rakhine communities and had confined their freedom of movement, thereby harming their livelihoods and capacity to acquire food. The Myanma military was also accused of the torture and ill-treatment of suspected insurgents, and of perpetrating sexual and gender-based violence. The FFM found that Myanmar should be brought before the International Court of Justice (ICJ) on the grounds of failure to honour its obligations as a signatory of the 1948 Genocide Convention. During September the CoI transferred its collected evidence on alleged atrocities perpetrated within Myanmar to the IIMM, which had been authorized by the HRC in September 2018, and was tasked with preparing files to be the basis of future criminal prosecutions under international law. In March 2021, following the Tatmadaw’s seizure of power in Myanmar in February, the IIMM stated that it was collecting evidence relating to arbitrary arrests, enforced disappearances, torture, and the use of force being perpetrated against civilians peacefully protesting the military coup. The Mechanism urged recipients of illegal orders to make direct contact with it, by secure means, to ensure eventual accountability for senior military personnel orchestrating human rights abuses. In that month the HRC adopted a resolution that requested the High Commissioner for Human Rights to monitor the ongoing situation in Myanmar, with a focus on accountability. In its fifth report, issued in June 2023, the IIMM emphasized its ongoing commitment to investigating sexual and gender-based crimes and crimes against children perpetrated against the Rohingya during 2016-17, and observed a dramatic increase since February 2021 in apparent serious international crimes committed in Myanmar, including systematic attacks against civilians. It noted that `millions’ of items of evidence had thus far been accumulated (such as documentation, forensic material, photographs, audio recordings, videos, geospatial imagery, and social media posts).</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Group of Human Rights Experts on Nicaragua (GHREN)</heading>
                    <p>The GHREN, established in accordance with a resolution of the HRC that was adopted in March 2022, was mandated to investigate human rights violations committed in Nicaragua since April 2018. A report by the Group that was published in March 2023 found that widespread violations of human rights, amounting to crimes against humanity—including arbitrary detentions, torture, extrajudicial executions and deprivation of Nicaraguan nationality—were being committed by the Nicaraguan authorities against civilians, for political reasons. The GHREN called on the international community to impose sanctions on the entities involved. In September the Group issued an update that emphasized that political opponents and human rights defenders were being pressurized to leave Nicaragua. Religious actors, particularly from the Roman Catholic Church, and academic institutions were also being systematically targeted.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Independent International Commission of Inquiry on the Occupied Palestinian Territories and Israel</heading>
                    <p>
          In May 2021 the HRC established an Independent International CoI to investigate humanitarian and human rights violations that were perpetrated leading up to and since 13 April 2021 in the Palestinian Territories, including East Jerusalem, and in Israel. The first report of the CoI, issued in June 2022, deemed the forced displacement of Palestinians, demolitions of Palestinian homes, expansion of Israeli settlements, settler violence, discrimination against Palestinians, and blockade of Gaza to be factors that were contributing to recurring cycles of violence. The report also noted that the Israeli occupation was used by the Palestinian (National) Authority as a justification for human rights violations and for failing to organize legislative and presidential elections, and that the Palestinian Islamist Hamas leadership in Gaza had shown no commitment to international humanitarian law. In October the CoI notably reported to the UN General Assembly that there were reasonable grounds to conclude that the Israeli occupation of Palestinian territory was unlawful under international law, owing to its permanence and to the Israeli Government’s de facto annexation policies. Consequently, in December the UN General Assembly requested the ICJ to issue an Advisory Opinion on the legal status and the consequences of Israel’s occupation of Palestinian territory. In May 2023 the CoI on Palestine issued its 
          <publ-name>Detailed findings on attacks and restrictions on and harassment of civil society actors, by all duty bearers</publ-name>
          . In September the CoI deemed that increasingly militarized law enforcement operations conducted by Israel in the West Bank and regular Israeli aerial attacks against targets in Gaza had been aimed at fragmenting Palestinian economic, political and social cohesion and maintaining the Israeli occupation. Hamas militants and other armed groups were urged to end all indiscriminate firing of munitions, including rockets and mortars, towards civilian communities in Israel, and to comply fully with international humanitarian and human rights law. The Israeli authorities were asked to respect Palestinians’ right to self-determination, to end the occupation of the Palestinian territory and Syrian Golan, to end all settlement construction and expansion in the West Bank, to act effectively to prevent violence by West Bank settlers against Palestinians, and to publish in full the Israeli security forces’ rules of engagement. Both sides were urged to end the practice of withholding bodies of captives (at that time Israel was reported to be withholding the bodies of 142 deceased Palestinian combatants and other persons suspected of having posed a threat to Israeli security; and the de facto authorities in Gaza were reportedly withholding the bodies of two Israeli soldiers).
        </p>
                    <p>In October 2023 the Commission reported that it was collecting and preserving evidence of war crimes perpetrated by both sides following the latest devastating Hamas-Israel conflict. It emphasized that all those who had targeted civilians must be held accountable. At the end of that month the Commission reiterated the urgent need for all parties to comply fully with international humanitarian and human rights laws.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading usage="ewyb edio">CoHR on South Sudan</heading>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio">The CoHR on South Sudan was authorized by the HRC in March 2016. The Commission stated grave concern in July 2021 over a series of systematic extrajudicial executions that had reportedly been perpetrated by government forces in Warrap State since March. In September the CoHR reported that more than US&#8201;$73m. in state resources had been systematically plundered by South Sudan’s elite since 2018. The CoHR issued a report in March 2022 that focused on conflict-related sexual violence against women and girls in South Sudan. In October 2023 the CoHR emphasized that, in advance of national elections scheduled for December 2024, the South Sudanese authorities should halt attacks on human rights defenders and journalists, and end unlawful media censorship and pervasive restrictions on civic and political activities.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>OHCHR Sri Lanka Accountability Project</heading>
                    <p>The High Commissioner established the Sri Lanka Accountability Project pursuant to a resolution adopted by the HRC in March 2021 on strengthening OHCHR’s capacity to collect and analyse data on human rights violations and related crimes in Sri Lanka; to advocate for victims and survivors; and to support relevant related judicial proceedings.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>Independent International FFM for the Sudan</heading>
                    <p> In October 2023 the HRC determined to establish an FFM, with an initial mandate of one year, to investigate crimes committed in Sudan in the context of the civil conflict that began there in April.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>CoI on Syria</heading>
                    <p>The CoI on Syria was established in accordance with an HRC resolution adopted in August 2011, and has subsequently issued regular reports and recommendations. In March 2023 the CoI reported that the parties to the conflict in Syria had continued to commit widespread human rights violations and abuses prior to the earthquakes that had devastated northern areas of the country in February, and that the emergency response initiative had been hindered by failure (of the parties to the conflict and also of the UN) to secure an immediate pause in hostilities, or to facilitate the delivery of life-saving aid. The adoption by the UN General Assembly in June of a resolution that authorized the establishment of an independent institution to clarify the fate and whereabouts of all missing persons in Syria was welcomed by the CoI. In September the CoI issued a report that addressed ongoing systematic patterns of ill treatment and torture in Syrian detention facilities. The CoI welcomed in November a landmark order by the ICJ that Syria take all measures within its power to prevent acts of torture or other cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment, and to take effective measures to ensure the preservation of related evidence.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>CoI on Ukraine</heading>
                    <p>
          In late February 2022 the High Commissioner confirmed that the Office’s Human Rights Monitoring Mission in Ukraine (HRMMU, first deployed in Ukraine, at the invitation of its Government, in 2014) would remain in that country following the military invasion by the Russian Federation, and would monitor and report on the evolving conflict situation. In early March the 49th session of the HRC adopted a resolution that condemned alleged violations of human rights arising from Russia’s aggression in Ukraine and established a CoI to investigate the situation. The CoI conducted its first mission to Ukraine in June. In September the CoI concluded that war crimes, and violations of human rights and of international humanitarian law had been committed there, mainly by the Russian military. The Commission detailed, 
          <i>inter alia,</i>
           the indiscriminate use of explosive weapons in populated areas and attacks on fleeing civilians; failure to protect civilians and civilian infrastructure through the placement of military forces and objects in or in close proximity to densely populated areas; illegal deportations of Ukrainians to Russia; and unlawful confinement, torture, summary executions, and sexual violence perpetrated in Russian-occupied areas. On 22 August the UN Secretary-General announced the composition of a new FFM 
          
          that had been established, at the request of the Russian and Ukrainian authorities, to investigate an attack on 29 July against a prison at Olenivka, Ukraine, which had caused at least 50 fatalities (culpability for which was attributed by each party to the conflict to the other). In March 2023 OHCHR stated deep concern over the recruitment to the Wagner Group, a Russian private paramilitary and security contractor, of detainees in Russian correctional facilities, who were reportedly being offered pardons and the transfer of remittances to relatives, in return for joining the organization to participate in the invasion of Ukraine. A report issued in October by the CoI detailed further evidence of indiscriminate attacks and war crimes perpetrated by the Russian authorities.
        </p>
                    <p>During 24 February 2022-31 December 2023 10,191 war-related civilian fatalities were recorded by the HRMMU in Ukraine. A further 19,139 civilians were reported to have suffered conflict-related injuries over that period.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>International FFM on Venezuela (FFMV)</heading>
                    <p usage="ewyb edio">The HRC established the FFMV in September 2019 to assess alleged violations of human rights committed since 2014. In September 2020 the FFMV’s first report stated that the Venezuelan state must bring to account members of the security forces and intelligence agencies that were accused of perpetrating arbitrary detentions and systematic torture, enforced disappearances, and extrajudicial executions. The FFMV’s second report, issued in September 2021, found that Venezuela’s judiciary lacked independence and that irregularities were occurring at all stages of the criminal process. Torture (including sexual violence), temporary enforced disappearances and arbitrary deprivation of life were reported, alongside widespread impunity. In October the FFMV stated deep concern over the recent death while in state custody of General Raúl Isaías Baduel (who had been detained since March 2017 and charged with treason and incitement to rebellion). The FFMV urged the Venezuelan authorities to undertake a thorough, transparent investigation into the cause of Baduel’s death, and to remedy judicial irregularities regarding his case that had been highlighted in the September report. In September 2022 the FFMV issued a report that provided an analysis of the chains of command in Venezuela’s military and civilian intelligence agencies, and the role of those agencies in suppressing dissent. In September 2023 the FFMV observed an intensification of state-imposed restrictions—including surveillance, harassment, threats, censorship and defamation—on the civic and democratic space of Venezuela’s individual human rights defenders, civil society organizations, labour unions, political parties and media. The FFMV noted that there appeared to be a continuity of personnel and modus operandi between the Bolivarian National Police’s recently established Directorate of Strategic and Tactical Actions (DAET) and its former Special Action Forces—which, prior to their dissolution in 2022, had been accused by the FFMV of involvement in gross violations of human rights.</p>
               </p-group>
               <p-group>
                    <heading>International Independent Expert Mechanism to Advance Racial Justice and Equality in the context of Law Enforcement</heading>
                    <p>The Mechanism (known as `EMLER’) was established by the HRC in 2021, following the High Commissioner’s issuance of a report on racial justice and equality that included a new four-point agenda aimed at ending systemic racism and human rights violations by law enforcement agents against Africans and people of African descent.</p>
               </p-group>
          </int-org-section>
